<p>
    Back when studying kinematics, <emph>kinematic graphs</emph>
    were one of the most crucial topics.
    Kinematic graphs described how position, velocity, and acceleration
    changed over time.
    They could be related to each other with qualitative patterns
    or with a quantitative rule called the <strong>fundamental theorem of calculus</strong>.
    Remember also that you didn't need to take a calculus class to understand the
    <strong>fundamental theorem of calculus</strong>!
</p>

<p>
    In this unit, on impulse, we will introduce the related concept of
    <emph>dynamic graphs</emph>.
    There are two main dynamic graphs: the <strong>momentum-time graph</strong>
    and the <strong>net-force-time graph</strong>.
</p>


